					   <td>

			
			
			



<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">
  
		<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
		<tr>
		    <td valign="top">
		     <p><font face="Verdana" size="3"><b>Article Title:</b>&nbsp;</font>
		     <font face="Verdana" size="2">Brad on data-loss, and compensation</font><br>
		     <a href = "../Subscribe.asp?DID=106866" ><font face="Verdana" size="2">[Subscribe to this document]</font></a></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr><td>&nbsp;</tr><tr>
		
		    <td valign="top"><div style= "padding:4;float: right"> <script language=JavaScript src=http://www.obsidian-tech.com/absolutebm/abmx.aspx?z=26></script></div><p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
		    <Blockquote>
<I>
Of course, when you're the victim of data loss, knowing how rare the occurance is doesn't help much -- it simply sucks to lose time in a game that's built around investing time.</I><P>

Good to know that you realize that sir.<P>

Then lets shift the burden of server crashes from your customers to Verant. At the very worst, we have players that lose 12 hours+ worth of gameplay (and loot) due to these crashes. I suggest you put in relaxed exp and items reimbursement policies to help people out. Please refer to my post above.<P>

Of course I do not suggest extremes like a level 10 paladins demanding a FA but something tangible that can be deemed appropriate. Lets have some refreshing (as compared to now) pro-active customer support from Verant for a change PLEASE!<P>

<B>The problem with that, uberVeazel, is that it just opens up a can of worms. A huge debate as to what's fair, what's not, what did I really lose, etc. would just occur.<P>

IMHO, it would be more of a mess and leave many people more unhappy overall than the data loss did.<P>

It would set a precedent that anytime anyone lost anything due to a problem that it would be reasonable to expect some sort of compensation. <P>

Having the manpower to do that is simply not going to happen, and being able to maintain consistancy (which is paramount in customer service) in that type of an operation is simply unrealistic.<P>

Our customer service teams (GMs & Guides) do their best with the resources and tools they have. Things will get better in the future as we bolster these teams with more people and better tools. But when it comes to data loss on a server-wide scale attempting to reimburse people for all they lost just can't be done. Nor can giving them something 'to make up for it'.<P>

-Brad</B><P>
</blockquote>
		    </font></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
